{# goal: Execute a bug-hunt probe using MCP tools against the target codebase, guided by the charter. #}
[inference]
template_type: KnowAct
lexicon_terms:
- probe
- explore
- search
- test
- verify
contract:
  input:
    charter: object
    target: object
    quality_criteria: string
    probe_depth: string
  output:
    probe_findings: string
    files_read: integer
    tests_run: integer
    probes_executed: integer
    crates_examined: array
energy_cap: 2048
visibility: Public
---
{# Template: bug-hunt/bug-hunt-probe.j2 #}
{# Functional Role: KnowAct — Execute a bug-hunt probe using MCP tools against the target codebase, guided by the charter #}
{# Implementation: Jinja2 prompt #}
{# Produces: probe_results #}
{# Phase 2 — PROBE (MCP tool-driven code exploration) #}
{# ℏKask v0.30.0 — Bug Hunting Expedition #}
{#
  This template provides probe guidance, but the actual probing is inherently
  agent-coordinated: the agent reads source files, searches for patterns, runs
  terminal commands (cargo check, cargo test, cargo clippy). This template
  formats the charter into actionable probe instructions and collects results.
#}

[inference]
temperature = 0.1
reasoning_effort = "low"
verbosity = "terse"
max_tokens = 1024
thinking_budget = "off"

You are formatting probe execution results. Do NOT generate fictional findings.
Only report what the agent actually discovered through MCP tool usage.

## Charter
```json
{{ charter | tojson }}
```

{% if probe_findings %}
## Probe Results (Agent-Executed)
{{ probe_findings }}

## Metadata
- Files read: {{ files_read | default(0) }}
- Tests run: {{ tests_run | default(0) }}
- Probes executed: {{ probes_executed | default(0) }}
- Crates examined: {{ crates_examined | default([]) | tojson }}
{% else %}
## No probe results available

The agent has not yet executed the probe. Using the charter's probe_instructions,
explore the target with available MCP tools:
- `file:read` — read source files
- `code:search` — search for bug patterns
- `terminal` — run cargo check, cargo test, cargo clippy

Bug patterns to search for:
- `.unwrap()` / `.expect()` in library code
- Public functions without contracts
- `unsafe` blocks without documented safety invariants
- Integer arithmetic without overflow protection
- `clone()` calls that may hide ownership confusion
- Mutable state without synchronization
- `panic!` or `todo!` in non-startup code

Apply diagnose pattern: reproduce before diagnosing, isolate one variable.
Apply adversarial pattern: try unexpected input orders, boundary values.
Apply cybernetic pattern: trace feedback loops, check Good Regulator, verify variety.

{% set beizer_runtime = ["timing", "integration", "structural"] %}
{% set charter_cats = charter.beizer_focus | default([]) %}
{% set needs_runtime = charter_cats | select("in", beizer_runtime) | list | length > 0 %}
{% set depth = probe_depth | default("static") %}

{% if (depth == "dynamic" or depth == "full") and needs_runtime %}
## Runtime Bug Patterns (BugStalker — Linux x86-64, debug build required)

When the charter targets timing, integration, or structural categories,
use BugStalker (`bs`) for runtime inspection. Skip if macOS/Windows.

Setup:
```bash
cargo build  # debug build required, NOT --release
bs ./target/debug/<binary>           # CLI mode
bs --oracle tokio ./target/debug/<binary>  # async code: enables Tokio oracle
```

Probe patterns:
- ASYNC DEADLOCK: `bs --oracle tokio ./target/debug/<binary>` — reproduce hang,
  inspect Tokio oracle panel for blocked tasks, trace `await` chain
- RACE CONDITION: `bs ./target/debug/<binary>` + `break <shared_state_site>` +
  `run` + `thread info` + `thread switch <n>` + `var locals` — inspect state
  across threads at the contention point
- STATE MACHINE VIOLATION: `bs ./target/debug/<binary>` +
  `break <transition_fn>` + `run` + `var <state_enum>` + `continue` — trace
  state transitions, verify invariants at each step
- MEMORY CORRUPTION: `bs ./target/debug/<binary>` + `break <crash_site>` +
  `run` + `var locals` + `arg all` + `reg info` — inspect memory at crash point
- POISONED MUTEX: `bs ./target/debug/<binary>` — break at mutex acquisition,
  inspect `var <mutex>.is_poisoned()` — identify which thread poisoned it
- UNEXPECTED POLLING: `bs --oracle tokio ./target/debug/<binary>` — watch
  scheduler activity, identify futures polled more often than expected

For each runtime probe, record: binary path, breakpoint locations, observed
variable states, thread states, and whether the behavior matches expectations.
{% endif %}

